column168: Our driver was delivering heating oil into a 5000 gallon tank.  The begining gauge readings on the customers tank was not accurate causing us to over fill the customers tank.  Some product leaked from vent onto the sidewalk.      Because of a bad gasket on the manhole cover on the customers tank product came out into a tank room where the oil was contained.  No sewers or soil involved.    Oil was pumped out  tank and ground was cleaned,and the NYC DEC notified.
column169: We continue to report problem deliveries to our customers including bad sounding devices and gauges.  We report bad fill connections.  We review the spill with our drivers and discuss if anything could have help prevent the spill

column168: This was the driver's second load of the same product to the customer with the same set of 2 inch hoses. When driver was unloading the product the discharge hose ruptured causing a spillage of product onto a concrete pad. The driver immediately shut off the pump and stopped anymore spillage of product onto the ground.  The cleanup was done by Conoco/Phillips personnel with oil dry and it was put in waste disposal drums.  After cleanup was complete, the driver used another hose that he had and completed his off loading.
column169: We will continue to test our hoses according to the rules set forth by our company. We will reinforce this policy with all our shop personnel at our Company Safety Meting

column168: While enroute to the intended waste disposal facility, the driver stopped at a truck stop to conduct a load check.  He noticed a small wet spot on the floor of the trailer.  The driver donned the appropriate PPE and contained the material with a suitable absorbent material.  He called his dispatcher and an emergency response crew was sent out to investigate the situation.  After donning the appropriate PPE, the crew overpacked the leaking drum into a suitable salvage drum, along with the absorbent material.  No material ever leaked onto the ground.  The drum had a small pinhole leak at the bottom where it was slightly corroded.  The load then continued to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: AT the time the container was accepted for transportation, the driver inspected the container and did not identify any structural integrity issues.  Bith the driver and the shipper location have been counseled on the importance of inspecting each ocntainer and takeing appropriate corrective actions should a damaged or suspect container be identified.

column168: During the loading proces, the loading hose "jumped" when air was drawn through the hose.  The movement of the hose, coupled with the very low ambient temperatures, caused a crack to form in the CPVC elbow at the cargo tank inlet.  In addition, the primary tank closure valve ("internal" valve) failed to seal completely, allowing the passage of material into the elbow and out through the crack.  Three cracks formed in the elbow proper along the rearward-facing vertical run of the elbow (see photos).  Vacuum was applied to the tank vessel to retain the material until a suitable trailer could arrive on-scene for transfer of the material.
column169: Following discussion with the trailer and valve manufacturers, additional support and isolation brackets are being added to the trailer of similar design in the transporter's fleet, and a modification of the valve control system is being retrofitted so as to provide for positive physical closure of the primary valve in addition to the "fail-safe" spring closure system.

column168: A box of four one gallon metal containers was loaded on its side between two pallets.  While in transit one of the lids popped off and material leaked out onto the trailer floor.  Material evaporated and left a stain type residue on the floor of the trailer.  The box that it was in was saturated and no markings or package information could be obtained.  Everything was placed in a salvage container for later disposal.
column169: The spill occured because the dockworker failed to load the container with orientaion arrows facing up.  This is clearly a human error form being in a hurry.  The situation was addressed with the dockworker and covered during a shift meeting to prevent future occurrences.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While BAX Global Inc. personnel was preparing to load freight at the BAX Global Toledo Hub, a release occurred.  The release was discovered from one (1) fiberboard box, which contained one (1) 1.4 kilogram cylinder of Oxygen, compressed.  BAX Global Inc. personnel moved the freight to the outside dock, opened the fiberboard box, and proceeded to allow the product to dissipate into the air.  The cause of the release is unknown.  Due to the nature of the product, no cleanup was required.  The empty cylinder, and fiberboard box were placed into one (1) 30-gallon salvage drum pending shipper disposition.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: The cause of the release is unknown.  Therefore no information is available on prevention.

The shipper did not use the proper packaging materials.The pails were stacked by the shipper directly onto the wood with no cardboard used. This resulted in the damage to the pail. column169: I would recommend that the shipper use more packaging material, like cardboard on the pallet to cushion the ride for the pails.

column168: While unloading trailer 463-6472 DSR Bruce Wilk discovered a 15 Gal drum has a liquid around the plug used to fillthe drum. He then notified me of the situation and I had Susan Adams call Chemtrac for handling procedures. Wewere told to recover the leaking drum into a salvage drum, which we did. DSR Wilk and myself loaded the leakingdrum into a salvage drum while wearing protective gloves and face shield. After being seal the salvage drum wasplaced in our OS&D area for further handling.
column169: It would seem that either the sealing plug failed or that when being filled a small amount of the liquid spilled onto therim of the drum. Either better control and proper cleaning of liquids or better plug testing prior to shipping.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURES, STABILIZED WITH ACIDS, WATER, AND NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT PEROXYACETIC ACID
column168: When unloading the trailer the dockworker noticed a small amount of liquid around the top of the drum, at which point he removed the fork lift from the trailer and contacted his supervisor. After the product was identified by the shipping bill, the trailer was pulled away from the dock. The Con-Way line haul safety department was contacted and a MSDS was obtained. It was determined that the material could be safely handled by our dock crew, the trailer was brought back up to the dock and the drum removed and placed into an empty trailer by it's self. On 03/09/2008,Randy Nolander from DeLaval Cleaning Solutions inspected the drum, checked both bungs on the drum with a bung wrench and cleaned up the small amount of liquid residue. He stated that the drum was in good condition for transport. Unable to determine when the leak occurred.
column169: It is imperative that the shipper ensures the product is ready for transportation prior to tendering to the carrier, thecarrier must double check the product before accepting the shipment.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE.  OUR DRIVER WAS PUMPING OFF FUEL INTO A ABOVE GROUND TANK AND THE DRIVER OVERFILLED THE TANK.  THE DRIVER HOOKED THE PUMP OFF HOSE ON TO THE INCORRECT TANK AND STARTED TO PUMP OFF AND OVER FILLED THE TANK.    THE DRIVER WAS GOING TO PUMP FUEL INTO TWO TANKS, 1 WAS THE WEST TANK AND THE OTHER WAS THE EAST TANK.  THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO MEASURE THE TANKS , BUT HE DID GET A VEENER ROOT PRINT OUT FOR BOTHE TANKS, BUT ACCIDENTALY HOOK THE 3300 GALLON COMPARTMENT ON TO THE WRONG TANK.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE TRUCK PUMP. HE THEN CONTACT THE CUSTOMER WHO WAS ON SITE AND THEY SPREAD OIL DRY DOWN AND BLOCKED THE FUEL FROM RUNNING OFF THE SITE. THERE WAS NO WATERWAYS OR STORM OR SEWER DRAINS FOR THE FUEL TO RUN TO. WE CONTACTEED VEOLIA ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND THEY CAME OUT TO CLEAN UP THE SITE. THERE WAS AN OHIO EPA INSPECTOR CALLED TO REVIEW SITE AND HE WAS PLEASED WITH THE CLEAN UP AND SOCI LEFT SITE. THE OHIO EPA REPORT NUMBER IS #0903-57-0587
column169: THE DRIVE WAS CONSULTED AND WAS TO MAKE SURE IN THE FUTURE THAT HE HAS THE TANKS IDENTIFIED PRIOR TO PUMPING FUEL OFF THE TANKER. WE HOLD QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS AND AT THESE MEETINGS WE WILL DISCUSS THE PROCEDURES TO MAKE SURE TO LOCATE THE CORRECT TANK PRIOR TO PUMPING OFF THE FUEL.    THIS DRIVER WAS GIVEN TIME OFF FOR THIS VIOLATION.

column168: March 12, 2009: At approximately 0920 hours, Conrail crew FM06 was traveling north on the West Track (m.p. 15.4) along the Chemical Coast Secondary with two locomotives (light) (units included CSX 8077 (trailing) and CSX 75) to couple to a draft of cars and bring them back to Port Reading (NJ) yard for switching.  Engineer and Engineer trainee in trailing unit, CSX 8077).  The engineer trainee failed to stop short of coupling, allowing short-nosed end of CSX 75 to couple to the draft of cars at an excessive speed.  Impact causing the engineer to strike his head inside the locomotive, requiring hospitalization (10 stitches, treated and released).    CSX 75 impacted A-end coupler of tank car GATX 17801, load Isopropyl Acetate, 3, UN 1220, II.  Impact forced the outboard end of A-end draft sill of GATX 17801 down, and inboard end of the A-end stub sill up, denting into the shell of the car.  Initial impact noted to have caused a leak from underneath the tank car's breadbox, housing the optional loading/unloading fittings.  REACT personnel arrived on scene at approximately 11am, and placed a containment trough under the middle of the car to contain leaking product that was cascading down the sides of the car from the bread box area (ultimately capturing approximately 5 gallons of product).  After the Carteret (NJ) Fire Department sprayed a sporadic layer of foam under the car, REACT personnel were permitted to access the car in an attempt to inspect and initiate possible securiement of leak.  Their inspection found all four (4) liquid line mounting flange securement nuts less then hand tight.  One nut was noted to be approximately 4-5 threads unsecured.  The minimal internal pressure was released to atmosphere by opening the air valve.  Once the pressure was released (in less than 1 minute), the leak ceased.  REACT tool tightened all four liquid line mounting flange securement nuts tool tight.        Due to the damage to GATX 17801 caused by the impact, the car was transferred on site.  Utilizing four (4) highway cargo tanks furnished by the ultimate customer, AllChem (for Kinder Morgan), a total of 145,660 lbs (20,063 gallons) was transferred.  Transfers began at 5:05pm, and concluded at 9:45pm.  Estimate approximately 10-20 gallons remain in the car and will be retrieved while cleaning and purging the car on a later date at Conrail's Port Reading, NJ yard.  Awaiting disposition on car whether it will be sent Home Shop for repairs, or scraped (on-site).
column169: As examined, it appears that, regardless of the handling and damaged caused by railroad handling, the car would not have released product (reported to be approximately 15 gallons prior to containment under the car) had the tank car's liquid line valve mounting flange securement nuts been appropriately secured in accordance with Sections 107.601(a)(6), 171.1(b)(4,11), 173.1(b), 173.24(a)(1), (b)(1,2), 173.31(d)(1)(ii,iii,iv), (d)(2) of CFR Title 49.  While the transfer of the remaining contents shipped in the car that ensued was resultant from the damage during Conrail's handling, the exhaustive and extensive emergency response by local, state and federal authorities could have been reduced and/or negated had there not been an emergency environment due to the release of a hazardous material.

column42: ENGINES INTERNAL COMBUSTION, OR ENGINES, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID POWERED
column168: AS EMPLOYEES IN THE UPS HUB IN MESQUITE, TX WERE SORTING PACKAGES, ONE PACKAGE WAS OBSERVED EMITTING A FLAME AS IT SLID FROM A CHUTE ONTO A CONVEYOR BELT.  USING A FIRE EXTINGUISHER, A PART-TIME SUPERVISOR EXTINGUISHED THE FLAMES, WHICH HAD SPREAD TO THE EXTERIOR OF THREE OTHER PACKAGES.  THE FIRE CAUSED NO INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO THE FACILITY.  UPON INSPECTION, THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN A CHAINSAW, FROM WHICH IT IS BELIEVED THAT FUEL LEAKED WITHIN THE PACKAGE SUFFICIENTLY TO PRODUCE FUMES THAT WERE IGNITED BY A STATIC SPARK WITHIN THE CONVEYOR AND SLIDE SYSTEM.
column169: REGULATIONS APPLICABLE TO THE SHIPMENT OF ENGINES, INTERNAL COMBUSTION MAY REQUIRE ADJUSTMENT.  THE CURRENT PROVISION OF 49 CFR 173.220(B)(1) ALLOWS UP TO 500 ML OF LIQUID FUEL TO REMAIN IN THE TANK AND FUEL SYSTEM.  HOWEVER, WHILE THAT AMOUNT OF FUEL MAY BE A RELATIVELY LOW RISK FOR VEHICLES, 500 ML OF FUEL IN A SMALL PIECE OF EQUIPMENT SUCH AS A CHAINSAW IS AMPLE TO CAUSE A SPILL WITHIN THE PACKAGE WHILE IT IS IN TRANSPORTATION UNDER THE PROVISIONS OF THE EXCEPTION IN 173.220(G)(1).  THIS INCIDENT SUGGESTS THAT REQUIREMENTS TO COMPLETELY DRAIN THE FUEL TANK MAY BE APPROPRIATE FOR SMALL EQUIPMENT THAT COULD BECOME INVERTED IN TRANSPORTATION, SINCE SPILLED GASOLINE CAN LEAD TO FIRES.

column168: A BNSF worker coupling air hoses in the railyard's bowl track reported a sulphur odor emanating from nearby GATX 8537 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car). A BNSF hazardous material responder was called to inspect GATX 8537. The responder reported that five of the six manway securement bolts were less than tool tight (four of these were finger loose). The responder properly tool tightened the loose securement bolts by 2100 hrs. CDT, 3/11/09. The small amount of product that escaped from the unsecured manway closure during normal switching operations had already cooled and solidified atop the tank shell. No spillage had impacted the ground.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: An inbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard revealed NATX 300697 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top fitting area of this tank car with leakage staining its side shell. NATX 300697 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The responder reported that the valve housing cover seal was intact. The seal was broken to inspect the valves under the cover. The liquid valve was observed leaking product from the valve handle's stem area. The liquid valve was in the closed position. The valve handle retention nut was tool tightened which immediately stopped the product leak at 1555 hrs. CDT, 3/14/09. All other valves and fittings were found to be secure. All spillage rapidly evaporated and no ground impact was evident. Response was concluded by 1605 hrs. CDT, 3/14/09.
column169: Ensure shippers pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Clean Harbors Aragonite LLC offered a shipment of incinerator slag for transportation in a non specification bulk bin.  At the time of loading, the driver inspected the container and all closures were in place and there was no evidence of leaking.  Upon arrival at the intended waste management facility, it was discovered that a clear liquid was leaking from the rear closure of the container.  Facility personnel immediately contained the release and absorbed all free liquids with a suitable absorbent.  In addition, additional absorbent was placed in the container to absorb any remaining free liquid that was visibile.  Once the laod was secured and the leak addressed, the container proceeded diretly to the off-loading area where the material was unloaded and processed for treatment and disposal.  All material generated in conjunction with the clean-up was disposed of at this location.  Please note that upn a detailed inspection, it was discovered that one of three bottom latches on the box was broken and it is believed that the abscence of this devise allowed a small amount of condensation to escape from the bottom seal.
column169: At the time the shipment was offered for transportation no evidence of residual liquid or damage was observed.  It is believed that two separate conditions exisiting that contributed to this release.  When loaded, the incinerator slag is hot and is routinely stored for a period of time prior to transportation.  It is during this time that the material cools dowm.  It is believed that once the tarp was placed over the container, condensation developed due to the continued cooling of the material.  This condensation migrated to the bottom closure where it escaped through the bottom closure.  The second condition that we believe contributed to the release was a borken latch.  It is believed that the driver failed to identify this deficiency during his pretrip inspection.    In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been retrained to ensure that a comprehensive inspection is conducted of both the container and the lading and that any deficient discovered is addressed before accepting the shipment for transportation.

column168: Three large cylinders (water capacity 1722 gallons each) were loaded in the trailer lying down. At some point during the transportation phase, the cylinders started toroll back and forth (front to back). The protective cover (that covers the on/off valve) came off the middle cylinder. It appears that the cylinder rubbed up against the scuff board on the lower portion of the trailer wall. This caused the protective cover to come off. Somehow the valve was bumped open and the gas started releasing from the cylinder. The chemical release was discovered when the trailer was backed up against the dock to be unloaded. Once it was determined to be safe, the valve was shut off to stop the release. It is unknown how much gas was released from the cylinder. The cylinders should have been properly blocked and braced to prevent movement in the trailer.
column169: Identify and re-train employee on proper blocking and bracing of freight in trailer.

column168: Pallet was discovered by me, Dennis Dainton, at 0115 by door 79. Pail on top was leaking inside of tightly shrunk wrap pallet. Investigated pro number and found itwas taken off of pup number 317-6619 which was breaking in door 69. Found DSR Donna Algar who breaking the load, and asked her if she noticed the damage tothe pail. She replied, she did not, so I walked her over to the pail. I told her to write it up damaged. It appears the pail was leaking during transit from XTM from the splatter of paint that appeared on the 50 gallon drum and another pail that was attached to the PLT that had dry paint on them. Plus, there was a good puddle already forming on top of bottom pail. The pail was dented on the inside facing the 50 gallon drum which caused a crimp and hole where the leaking was coming from. After calling both Linehaul and Chemtrec. I continued clean up by placing 5 gallon pail in small salvage drum and cleaned up the spill from the top of pail that was below the damaged pail. Placed salvage drum in OS&D.
column169: Where you are able to do so, suggest or describe changes (such as additional training, use of better packaging, or improved operating procedures) to help preventrecurrence. Provide recommendations for improvement to hazardous materials transportation beyond the control of your individual company. Continue on additional sheets if necessary.I believe the pail was hit by other freight being loaded and the DSR loading probably not knowing there was damage done. There was no physical damage to outside of pail that was against shrink wrap, and there was no damage to the shrink wrap itself. The pallet was very tightly shrinked wrapped and the unloading DSR claimedthat there was dunnage around the shipment before it was unloaded from the trailer. Possible cause of damage could have been the freight being pushed against the plywood while loading causing the pail to get pressed into the 50 gallon drum causing dent and crimped hole, causing a very small leak.

Shipper tendered container, PAFX545071-8/WB2190003, to ocean shipper on 3/13/09 in Tacoma for loading on the Horizon Anchorage, AZ747N, for transit to Anchorage.  Vessel arrived in Anchorage on 3/17/09. During a random inspection on 3/18/09 it was discovered that UN1956, was undeclared. Documentaion was updated and pertinent parties notified.
column169: Shipper must review shipment periodically while loading to ensure that paperwork is correct, to what was actually loaded. This should be completed prior to tendering load to teh trucker and the ocean carrier.

column168: THE  DRIVER HAD A SMALL RELEASE OF # 2 HEATING OIL AS A RESULT THE TANK BEING OVER-FILLED. THIS WAS CLEANED AND CONTAINED,THERE WAS NO ENTRY INTO STORM DRAINS OR WATER WAYS. MDE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE DRIVER HAD A SMALL SPILL DUE TO THE O-RING BEING PINCHED DURING THE DELIVERY. THERE WAS NO MORE THAN 1 GAL. OF # 2 HEATING OIL THAT WAS RELEASED. MDE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Driver to make delivery of product to customer using carrier pump and product hoses. Driver said that after he started his product pump the discharge hose ruptured about 10 inches from the fitting end at the customers connection. spill was contained within the customers spill basen under the customers receiving line.  The hole in the product hose is about 1/8 inch centered in an abrasion of about 1/2 inch. Incident duration of about 1/2 hour driver replaced hose and continued delivery without incident.
column169: The effected hose has been sent to shop for inspection.  The carrier has a product hose testing program in place and drivers are trainer to inspect hoses prior to there use. The driver in question said he did inspect the hose and it looked in good shape.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: First Responder at level one reported the unauthorized release at about 08:00 on 03-02-2009. First Responder at level five [FR-V] made assessments, contained the spill, controled the release, stopped the release, kept spill on property and out of all sources to navigable waterways.    At about 12:30 FR-V notified Cal-OES, Local CUPA, local FRA Inspector, Local PUC Inspector, Boss and Shipper of unauthorized release of HM.    The shipper arrived the same day at 23:00. FR-V showed them the hot zone and we left the site for the night.    On 03-03-2009 at 06:30 hours the clean-up operation began. The FR-V secured all heavy equipment and the decision was made to have the shipper bring in their own contract response team NCR Environmental Services.    The hot zone was neutralized with a soda ash solution and the contaminated soil was removed from the site as a NON-RCRA Hazardous Waste, Solid.    The volume in the rail tank car was brought down and the shipper replaced the rupture disc.
column169: The shipper should have known that the rail tank car was overfilled and should have addessed it before offering it for shipment. The carriers [the Canadian RR and the UPRR] both should have red tagged this car as both carriers are bound under the HMR to weigh all HM shipments.    The car should have never made it to the consignee, all systems that were put in place to stop this from happening were not followed.    UPC is in the process of helping all of them in their efforts to comply with the HMR.

column168: The Drum was recieved at 086 damaged. I can only assume that it was being moved with a forklift.  The hole in the top portion of the drum was clearly caused by a forklift blade.
column169: Use the proper equipment when transferring drums.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: The Veolia forklift operator was offloading a trailer destined for the Veolia - Menomonee Falls facility. While removing a pallet from the trailer, the forlift operator pushed the forks of the lift truck in too far which resulted in puncturing two 55 gallon drums of paint and oil from a household hazardous waste collection facility. The operator immediately contained the spill with oil dry, placed the leaking drums into a salvage drum and placed the clean-up materials into the salvage drum as well.
column169: The operator was retrained on the safe operation of the lift truck, including knowing where the end of the forks are at all times.

column25: Clean Harbors Env. Ser. (c/o Spring Grove Resources)
column168: On March 6, 2009 at approximately 00:16hrs, personnel in the Transflo yard in Cincinnati, OH, discovered GATX53924, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids, NOS (Tolulene, Xylene) leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and crews were vacated from the area.  The shipper, Clean Harbors Environmental, was notified and dispatched their own crews to the scene. Upon arrival, Clean Harbors personnel found that the manway bolts were less than tool tight. Clean Harbors representatives loosened all bolts and refastened in a star pattern with near equal force on all manway bolts and the leak stopped.  The car was released to destination. There was no Chemtrec involvement. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5(5+3+1) X (2+0) = 90
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 03/09/2009 at 10:55 hrs., personnel in the CSXT rail yard in Waycross, GA discovered GATX 200408, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids, NOS (Crude Sulfate Turpentine) leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was switched out of the bowl track and placed over the chemical spill pan and the shipper, Domtar Paper Co LLC was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2009-03-09-00068). CSXT hazardous material sentinels, Tommy Pearson and Ira Walker, responded to the scene and found the bottom outlet operating handle hanging down in the open position and product was leaking from the bottom outlet valve bell cap. The operating handle was raised and pinned in the closed position which stopped the product release.  The bottom outlet valve bell cap was then tightened. The car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.                5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80  Cause Code: 148
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On March 11th at 11:50 hours, personnel in the CSXT Cartersville Yard discovered ETCX630102, a loaded tank car of Methanol leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Dupont Denemours was notified via Chemtrec (Report Number 2009031100078).  SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the container was leaking due to the sample line left in the open position and the closure plug less than tool tight.  SWS representatives closed the sample line valve, securely tightened the closure plug with a wrench and the leak stopped.  The tank car was decontaminated and released to destination.      An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did require a special shipping move to isolate the railcar.    Cause Code: 513  NARRI:  5(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 03/18/09 at 12:54 hours, FRA Inspector Gary Burke, was performing an inspection at the CSXT Erwin yard facility.  During that inspection, he discovered ADMX 30626, a loaded tank car of Alcohols N.O.S., leaking vapor from around the top of the vacuum relief device. The tank car was isolated and the shipper was notified.  A CSXT emergency response contractor, RESCAR, was dispatched to the scene to make repairs. Upon arrival, RESCAR personnel removed the vacuum relief device and replaced it with a plug. The shipper, Archer Daniels Midland, has requested movement approval from the FRA to send the car to destination.        NARRI :  2 (5+3+0) * (2+0) = 32  Cause Code: 466
column169: No additional comments.

column168: While unloading trailer material handler discover this drum that had cracked during transit which in turn contributed to the unintentional release. Apparently the drum was staged onto a pallet and during the course of transit it shifted and partially fell between the wood stringers of the pallet which in turn caused it to crack and leak. Spilled material was neutralized and cleaned with sorbent material and placed into a recovery container.
column169: Dunnage on the pallet such as a piece of cardboard could have helped the drum from falling inbetween the wood stringers as could have better securement.

column168: When unloading freight driver discovered three boxes that had been either crushed or punctured by forklift blade when they were originally loaded into the trailer. Basically, the material was dried so no cleanup was necessary - the three boxes were placed into a recovery container.

column168: Upon arrival of CX090/17Mar, a CX DFW staff member noticed a strong smell coming from the back of the aircraft.  After removing some of the pallets, our staff noticed fluid on the aircraft floor and on PMC96551CX loaded in position HL.  Because of the strong smell our staff made the decision to evacuate the aircraft immediately.  The fire department was immediately notified.  And although we made several trials to contact the FAA, we were not able to do so until early morning on the 18th.                                                                              Because the incident occurred inside the aircraft, the Fire Department was not involved in the cleaning.  Instead a private company, Hulcher Services Inc., was hired to contain, clean and dispose of any toxic materials.             The shipment in reference was unloaded from the aircraft and each drum was checked for leakage.  Two drums were found to be leaking and were disposed off in a special container later collected by the Hazmat company.  Both drums had structural damage caused by too much weight placed on top of them.  Fissures were small and almost not noticeable.
column169: Our headquarters in HKG is currently reviewing this case and will notify us of their findings.  Nevertheless we have suggested to our operational department to limit the amount of weight placed on top of any steel drum.

column168: The battery was on the shipper's pallet and tied against the wall of the trailer when it tipped over enroute to delivery in Salt Lake City.  The pallet failed under the weight of the 1755 Ibs. battery and tipped over, spilling approximately 10 gallons of fluid in the rear of the trailer.  The spill was cleaned by Enviro-Care, a third-party hazmat response team.
column169: The cause of the spill was an overweight battery (1755lbs) on a pallet too small to manage the load.  Although the freight was tied down, the shifting of weight was too much stress on the pallet, ultimately causing it to collapse.  In turn, the battery's weight broke the twine and spilled onto the trailer floor.  A discussion of the incident will take place with the driver regarding heavy freight and hazmat. Further discussions will include discussions on load factors for twine and other fastening devices.

column168: On 3/24/09, driver went to Enterprise in Breaux Bridge, La to load stenched propane for customer. The driver was in the process of loading and the pressure on the trailer got above 215 lbs psi and began to release pressure around the rear dome lid of the trailer. The pressure went from 215 lbs to 205 lbs and the leak stopped. when the incident occured the driver immediately stopped loading and notified the operator at the terminal and DEQ and state police, along with La Hazmat were notified. There was no injuries or property damage due to release and another vehicle was dispatched to location to offload trailer. The trailer was offloaded and flared down at the plant and was released. The incident was the rear manhole gasket failed due to a manufactured component that was approved for opertion of this vessel. The release lasted about 3 minutes.
column169: The failure was due to a manufactured component that is approved for use with this type of vessel. Recommend better testing of the components used for this equipment.

column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUSMATERIALS, PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOODAND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TOEASILY DAMAGED. TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING INHAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ONTOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column169: DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE THAT PACKAGING TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING.  SEAMS, LIDS, VALVES AND OTHER CLOSURES MUST BE TIGHT TO PREVENT LIDS FROM LOOSENING AND RELEASING THE LIQUID. THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND/OR TOTES MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION.  IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE BEING ALLOWED TO MOVE.  TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER OR PACKAGING MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED.  DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: While conducting a transfer of ethanol utilizing Ethanol Pump #PM9982, approximately 5 gallons of product impacted the asphalt surface due to hose failure. While monitoring the transfer, the loader observed product escaping from the hose. The transfer was immediately stopped and the situation investigated. The loader found that the cause of the product release was a compromised section of hose located underneath the protective sleeve used to prevent abrasions to the hose from dragging on the ground. A spill pan was immediately put into place and sand was applied to the area to contain the product that was released. The hose was replaced immediately. The released product was cleaned up and placed in a 55 gallon drum that is staged on property for ethanol disposal.
column169: Continued diligence in performing the daily and monthly inspections on the hoses. Emphasis will be placed on looking closely at the areas around the abrasion sleeve.

column168: On March 13th at 13:51 hours, personnel in the CSXT Davis Yard discovered TILX199616. a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S. was leaking from the top of the railcar.  The car was isolated and Chemtrec (report number 2009031300120) assisted in contacting the shipper, Iroquois Bio Energy.  A CSXT emergency response contractor, Rescar, was dispatched to the scene to secure the railcar.  Upon arrival, Rescar representatives found that three (3) of eight (8) manway securement bolts/nuts were less than tool tight.  Rescar personnel tightened the bolts/nuts and the leak stopped.  The car was decontaminated and forwarded on to destination.      An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not required for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.  Cause Code:  200  NARRI:  5(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On March 15th, 2009 at approximately 10:45 hours, personnel in the CSXT Buffalo Frontier Yard smelled an odor of ammonia.  The yard crew discovered CWBX 300000, a residue tank car of UN1005, Anhydrous Ammonia, leaking from around the protective housing. The car was isolated (NYS-DEC report 0813505 and Chemtrec 20090315-00011) and the shipper was notified. SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the PRD-Valve O-Rings had deteriorated.  SPSI personnel replaced the o-rings and prd-valve cap.  The leak was secured and the car will be released for transport upon an FRA Movement Approval number being issued.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed or required for this incident.  Note: This incident did require a special shipping move, from classification track 43 to Flexiflo north track Frontier Yard isolation area.  Cause Code:  414  NARRI: 5(4+9+0) X (2+0) = 130
column169: No additional comments.

column168: We had a report of an sulfur acid spill about 6:00 AM on March 10,2009 from ASARCO Security Personnel, Hayden, AZ.  At that point the AZ DPS became involved, the problem was that other Transpiration Companies were hauling out of the same location beside B.J. Cecil Trucking, Inc. which made it hard to determine who had the spill.  It was determined from the outbound scale tickets by the AZ DPS that it was either B.J. Cecil or Bulk Carriers.  B.J. Cecil went ahead and ordered the clean up through Environmental Response, Inc., 2202 W. Medtronic Way, Suite 108, Tempe, AZ 85281. B.J. Cecil’s suspected truck was contacted and the driver insisted that he had did his safety checks and there was not leaks.  But the next day after the unit had delivered that load and came back to the terminal that there was residual evidence on the rear on the trailer that this unit had cause the spill.  We think the driver had not securely closed the dome lid to prevent a leak.  The leaks occurred on the uphill grades(2 miles)for a distance of 10 miles, with the release of 9 to 10 gals. of Sulfuric Acid.
column169: Increase driver awarness and communication.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was being loaded for transportation to the intended waste management facility.  During the loading operation, the driver identfied a closure on the side of the container that he had not seen before.  The driver inspected the container and based on the markings on the container determined that the container was a UN rated container.  At the time of the inspection, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed.  Once loaded, the driver proceeded to the next pick-up location on the shipper's propoerty.  When the driver arrived at the second pick-up location, he re-inspected the containers previously loaded and identified that approximatley 8 ounces of liquid had escaped from the container from the closure device.  The closure device was tightened and no furhter evidence of leaking was observed.  The shipper absorbed all free liquids and placed it into a container for propoer disposal.
column169: I order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been re-instructed to physically check the closure devices o each container prior to accepting for transportation.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous materials was enroute to the intended waste management facility identified on the shipping paper.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine comfort stop at a truck plaza and while at this location, conducted a load check.  Upon inspecting the load, it was discovered that a device (load bar) used to secure the shipment dislodged allowing one container to fall from the skid it was sitting on releasing approximatley 10 ounces of material from the top closure.  The driver immediately secured the scene and contacted his home dispatcher.  In additon, a courtesy notification was made to both the State of TN Department of Envirinmental Protection and the truck stop manager to alert them to the incident.  A local emergency respnse crew was dispacted to the scene to assist the driver reposition the shipment, ensure all closures were in place and secure, clean-up the minimal amount of liquid released and re secure the load securement devices before the driver continued on his trip.
column169: IN order to prevent a recurrence, the driver was re instructed to ensure that when accepting a shipment, he is obligated to inspect the load secureent devices to not only ensure they are in place but that they are adequate for the type and size of containers being securd.  Furthermore, he was advised to request that when odd size containers are loaded on a skid, that a supplemental securement device such as shrink wrap or banding is to be used to prevent movement while in transit.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean harbor's in transit storage yard located in Bristol, CT.  During this stop, a load check was performed and a 1 gallon release of material was identified from one of the containers.  Facility personnel immediately activated the internal emergency reposne action plan which included an evacuation of the specific loading dock where the truck was parked, notification of local and state officials and dispatch of an emergency response team.  Upon arrival, the containers were inspected and it was discovered that a small pinhole developed on the bottom of one of the containers. It is beleived that the structural integrity of the container was compromised due to the presence of rust.  The emergency response team placed the damaged container into a suitable slavage drum along with all material used to absrob and clean up the spilled material.  In additon, the remaining 14 drums were also placed into salvage drums as a precaution.  Once resolved, the truck was allowed to continue to the intended waste management facility.
column169: IN order to repvent a recurrence, the driver has been reonstructed that it is his responsibility to not only inspect the closures of the containers but the structural integrity of each package before he accounts for transportation.  Furthermore, he is responsible to ensure that before a container is palced on his vehicle that all necessary precautions are taken to ensure each container is in a condition that will stand up to the rigors of transportation.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering gas to a client location. While unloading the driver noticed fuel beginning to leak from the stick port of tank #1. The driver immediately stopped the flow of product. The driver contained the spill on concrete but due to heavy rains and flash flooding some product did reach drains. The stick readings and store's automatic readings show that the product should have been able to fit without exceeding the 90% fill capacity. column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility when the driver made a routine stop at a Clean Harbors’ 10-day in transit storage facility.  While at this location, it was discovered that a compressed gas cylinder containing a contact adhesive had a small pinhole in the sidewall of the container that released an estimated 8 ounces of contact adhesive before the adhesive dried and sealed the leak.  Facility personnel secured the container dispatched a field service crew to re containerize the material before continued transportation.  While waiting for the crew to arrive, a courtesy telephonic report was made to the Texas Department of Environmental Quality (report No. 20090938) to advise them of the situation and explain the corrective actions being taken.    Once the field service crew arrived, the crew emptied the contents of the cylinder into an alternate container and removed the vale of the cylinder.  All clean-up debris, product and the empty cylinder body was placed into a suitable container and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility where it was received and properly disposed of.
column169: The cylinder showed signs of abrasion near the pinhole leak in the side which indicated it had rubbed against another object during transportation.  The origin driver was instructed to use better care when loading objects for transportation and to take appropriate corrective actions should a container be observed to show signs of suspected damage.

AT AN APPROX DISTANCE OF 300 TO 400 FEET (A DISTANCE I'M UNSURE OF) I NOTICED THE PICKUP DRIFT INTO MY DRIVING LANE THE DRIVER APPEARED TO BE SLUMPED FOREWARD LIKE HE WAS PICKING SOMETHING UP.  I GAVE HIM A SECOND OR TWO TO TAK CORRECTIVE ACTION, THINKING HE WAS PICKING SOMETHING UP AND THAT HE'D PULL HIS HEAD UP AND CORRECT THE DIRECTION OF HIS PICKUP.  IT BECAME CLEAR IN A SECOND OR TWO THAT HE WASN'T GOING TO PULL HIS HEAD UP AND CORRECT THE DIRECTION OF HIS PICKUP, AT THIS POINT I TOOK EVASSIVE ACTION BY HEADING TO THE RIGHT HAND DITCH.  AN I ENTERED THE DITCH I THOUGHT I HAD AN ANGLE THAT WOULD ALLOW ME TO MISS A COLLISION WITH HIM.  HOWEVER, I WAS WRONG. HE DROVE AT FULL SPEED INTO THE LEFT FRON SIDE OF MY TRUCK DISLODGING MY FRONT END CARBERATION TAK, PUNCTURING THE CARBERATION TANK CAUSING THE GAS TO LEAK OUT, AND SENDING MY TRUCK ROLLING INTO A NEARBY PASURE.  AS THE TRUCK ROLLED TO A REST THE FILL HOLE PIPE WAS CRACKED ON THE BOBTAIL CAUSING A  LEAK.  I HEARD THE LEAK LEAKING PRIOR TO ITS IGNITION, AND I HEARD THE GAS IFNITE.  I CRAWLED FROM THE CAB AND TO SAFETY WITH THE HELP OF A PASSERBY.  WHEN THE FIRST RESPONDERS ARRIVED I GAVE INSTRUCTION TO THEM TO PLACE WATER ON THE BOBTAIL, AT THE LIGHT WIND THAT DAY WAS CARRYING THE GAS & FLAME AWAY FROM THE VESSEL.  I FELT THIS WAS THE MOST PRUDENT PLAN OF ACTION AT THAT POINT TO KEEP THE AREA SAFE.  SHORTLY THEREAFTER I WAS REMOVED FROM THE ACCIDENT SCENE BY AMBULANCE UNAWARE OF FUTHER ACTION TAKEN.

column168: A trailer filled with empty cylinders of ammonia anhydrous arrived at the terminal after pick-up from the shipper.  The trailer was parked in the yard with the door closed.  An employee who walked past the trailer told one of the supervisors that the trailer had an odor.  The supervisor and freight manager approached the trailer that was still in the yard, and opened the door.  Upon opening the door the supervisor and freight manager immediately closed the door due to the strong odor.  The safety department was contacted, and the safety manager told the supervisors not to unload the trailer, and an emergency clean-up vendor would be called.  An MSDS for the material was obtained, and the emergency response vendor dispatched a crew to the terminal.  The emergency response vendor (BellonEnvironmental) on the phone instructed us to move the trailer (with the door closed) to another section of the yard that was not populated.  No one was evacuated from the building since the cylinders stayed in the trailer outside.  Upon the emergency clean-up crew's arrival, it was determined that the cylinders were not full.  However, one had a small amount of frozen residue on the valve that indicated that a residual amount had purged inside of the trailer due to it being warm that day.  The amount would have been a fraction of the full contents; however, it was trapped inside the trailer and caused a strong odor. All of the valves were open upon pick-up from the shipper, so the crew closed all of the valves and let the trailer set open over night and into the next day. The shipment was moved to destination the following day. Our company was not aware that the valves were open upon pick-up, and the cylinders were  supposed to be completely empty due to them being open and aired for for 3 days before the pick-up. It is hard to know how much was actually released; however, one of the the emergency response crew lead man at the scene said that he would estimate the release was less than 10 pounds.
column169: The shipper should not be shipping cylinders with open valves, even if they are supposed to be empty.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Shipper notified BNSF that NATX 33091 (DOT 112J340W tank car) was inadvertently released loaded from their facility lacking final preparations toward its pre-trip inspection. The BNSF train with NATX 33091 entrained was stopped on the main track near a remote area for inspection by a BNSF hazardous material responder. An audible vapor hiss could be heard when the BNSF responder approached NATX 33091. The responder found the valve protective housing cover not pinned or sealed. When the protective cover was lifted for valve inspection, product odor was detectable. The responder's inspection revealed that 2 of the 4 mounting flange bolts at the base of the vapor valve were less than tool tight (approximately 1/2 turn each). The responder tool tightened the flange bolts until no further vapor hiss and product odor was evident. No liquid product release was observed. Securement was completed by 1915 hrs. CST, 3/04/09. NATX 33091 was released to proceed in the train to the next major terminal (Springfield, MO) for follow-up inspection by shipper contract responders. The shipper contract responders inspected and re-tightened all flange bolts to 250 foot pounds of torque. All other valves and fittings were checked for securement and tested for leakage. After finding no exceptions, the valve housing cover was repinned and sealed. Shipper contractor response was concluded by approximately 1600 hrs. CST, 3/05/09.  Due to the BNSF main track service interruption during the initial response, nine BNSF trains were delayed averaging five hours with six of these trains requiring replacement train crews.
column169: The shipper is reviewing internal processes to ensure future hazardous material shipments are not released into transportation prior to their final pre-trip preparations and inspections.

column168: PROX 41140 was reported leaking in the West Colton rail yard. The leak was caused by a loose pressure relief device. Seven out of eight nuts were missing from the base of the pressure relief device flange. The nuts were replaced and tightened. The tank car was decontaminated and released.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Train LLL66-06 derailed 5 cars. Tank car GATX 40461, a load of molten sulfur, struck the north east corner of the bridge on Bayou Plaquemine. The impact caused a vertical gash at the body bolster of the tank car. The B end, right body bolster was sheared off. The gash was approximately 4 long and 6 wide and molten sulfur began leaking out as several pencil sized streams at first. Eventually a large volume of product streamed out until the sulfur began to cool and solidify forming a large stalactite on the side of the tank car. The molten sulfur that released coated the immediate area of the bridge and into the water of the bayou, and then it cooled, solidified and settled on the bottom at the edge of the bank.  GATX 40461 remained on the bridge until repairs could be completed to the approach. This car was re-railed and taken by rail to Addis.  No more sulfur leaked from the tank.    Train LLL66-06 derailed 5 cars. The train was travelling south when the seventh car from the power, tank car GATX 40461, a load of molten sulfur, struck the north east corner of the bridge on Bayou Plaquemine.  ASOX 296016 was next and fell off the north approach to the east down a 40 (app) dump, landing on the A end causing a large dent in the head.  This damage resulted in a crack that allowed a small vapor release. The release was detectable as a slight odor. ASOX 296016 was re-railed and taken to the yard at Addis, LA.  Sorbent materials (pads) were placed inside the tank to preclude the release of any liquid.
column169: None at this time.

column168: During random tank car inspections, ACFX 200354 was found to be releasing vapor from the vacuum relief valve.  At the shippers request, a plug was installed in place of the vacuum relief valve and an FRA one-time movement approval obtained.    ACFX 200403 was found to be releasing vapor from the vacuum relief valve.  Phone conversations with the car lessor (Aventine Renewable Energy) informed them of the problem and they requested the valve be removed and replaced with a solid plug.  The plug was installed and following receipt of an FRA one-time movement approval, the car continued in transportation for requalification.
column169: Remove vacuum relief valves or ensure proper maintenance.

column168: A BNSF westbound train operating on the main track was stopped after an undesired emergency or application of train air brakes was experienced. The ensuing train inspection uncovered two train air line defects and these were corrected. Also during the train inspection, ECLX 16047 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was observed dripping product from the bottom outlet area of this tank car. ECLX 16047 was setout of this train at Williams Jct., AZ for a detailed inspection and securement correction by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The BNSF responder arrived shortly after ECLX 16047 was setout of the train. The responder observed product seepage around the primary bottom outlet's threaded connection to the tank car's outlet. The bottom outlet also had a bottom operated 2 inch unloading ball valve outlet affixed to it, but no product seepage was observed from this closed and securely plugged outlet. The responder inspected the sealed top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV) securement and found the operating rod was not in the closed position by 1/4 turn. The responder fully closed the TOBOV and product seepage at the bottom outlet connection stopped. Securement was completed by approximately 1640 hrs. MDT, 3/14/09. Non-dried spillage around the bottom outlet was wiped. Minimal ground impact was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: BNSF trainmaster reported UTLX 41028 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) dripping product down its sideshell while in the railyard. BNSF contract hazardous material responders were dispatched to inspect UTLX 41028 and correct any securement deficiencies. Responders reported that the leak source emanated from under the valve housing cover that had its seal intact. The valve housing cover was opened and the responders observed a slow product leak from the liquid valve's closure plug connection. The liquid valve was found to be partially open and its closure plug was not tool tight. The valve was closed which stopped any further product leak. The closure plug was removed and Teflon tape was applied to its threads. The plug was reinserted and properly tool tightened. Spillage that didn't evaporate was wiped. The valve housing cover was closed and sealed with seal numbered 433304. Securement was completed by 0310 hrs. CDT, 3/21/09. No ground impact was evident for this release.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: While driver was unloading product into tank, the ball and check valve rose and became stuck to the pipe, closing off the vapor release of the tank causing pressure to build up, and the gas to be released.     The investigation revealed that on the opposite end of the tank from the fills a 3" toggle cap was off and allowd product  to escape while delivered into tank.     It appears the maintenance personnel used pipe dope on the top fitting of the valve , and a glob of the pipe dope landed on the ball of the valve causing a release of product.
column169: A full investgation was conducted and it was determined that inadequate maintenance caused the release. Delivery was suspended to station until problem was corrected. Maintenace department notified, immediatley, and tank has since been properly repaired.

column168: WEARING PROPER PPE I, MICHAEL SCHULTZ RESPONDED TO A BOX THAT WAS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR IN BAY 60 AT 20:00. THE DECISION TREE AND MARKINGS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX LED ME TO THE NON-FLAMMABLE GAS RESPONSE SHEET. THEIR WAS A LITTLE POWDER THAT LEAKED OUT THE BOX AND INSIDE THE BOX WAS A DRY CHEMICAL FIRE EXTINGUISHER. SO I PLACED THE BOX INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY AND SWEPT UP THE POWDER AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO THE PSC AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. column168: LOCAL SORTER LARRY SCOTT WAS SORTING SMALL PKGS.  PACKAGE WAS BEING SHIPPED 3-DAY AIR.  WHEN HE PICKED IT UP HE THOUGHT IT SOUNDED LIKE AEROSOL CANS, BROUGHT IT TO ACCEPTANCE AUDITOR JAYNE TILLEY TO SEE IF IT COULD BE SHIPPED.  I, JAYNE TILLEY, CHECKED CONTENTS: IT WAS A BATTERY TERMINAL PROTECTOR IN AEROSOL CAN.  SO I CALLED HAZ HELP DESK.  CHARLENE TOLD ME I NEEDED AN MSDS TO DETERMINE NEXT STEP.  TRIED TO CONTACT SHIPPER; NO ANSWER, SO I CALLED 3E COMPANY.  I THEN CALLED HAZ HELP DESK BACK.  SHE ENTERED IT AS AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT AND TOLD ME TO TAKE PICTURES OF ALL SIDES AND EMAIL THEM AND ENTER IT IN ETT DAMAGE INPUT AND THAT AN EMAIL WOULD BE SENT TO RICH CLEMENT, MY CENTER MANAGER.  I FILLED OUT CHECK LIST TO BE SENT TO HAZ COOR. AND BUS/DEV.  THE CAN WAS NOT DAMAGED AND NEITHER WERE THE OTHER ITEMS BEING SENT WITH IT.  I AM HOLDING THE PKG IN OUR DECLARED HAZMAT HOLD AREA UNTIL FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a Clean Harbor's 10 day intransit facility located in West Sacramento, CA for the purpose of pikcing up additonal materials for continued transportation.  Upon arrival at the intransit facility it was discovered that approximatley 1 pint of material had escaped from either a loose or damaged closure device on the IBC.  The material was contained within the trailer and did not escape to the environment.  Upon discovery, facility personnel immedialtey placed a suitable absorbent material down to absorb the material that escaped from the package and called in an emergency response team.  Upon arrival, it was determined that the safest course of action was to transfer the material in the leaking container into an alternate package.  This component of the response was done without incident.  In addition, approximately 200 pounds of clean-up debris (absorbent material, decontamination media and disposable personal protective equipemtn) was generated during the course of the transfer, clean-up and decontamination operation and placed into a UN rated package for disposal.   At the conclusion of the response activity, the vehicle was dispatched to the intended waste management facility where the all material, including the original IBC, was processed and disposed of.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the loading facility and the driver have been reinstructed to ensure that all packages are thoroughly inspected prior to offerif for or acceting for transportation.  This inspection includes a review of the physucal condtion of the container and all related closure devices.  It is believed that due to the age of the container, the closure device became loose during the course of transportation allowing a small anount of materialto escape from the top closure and run down the side of the container onto the trailer floor.  At the time to load was accepted for transportaiton there was no evidence of leaking but it has been stressed to both the loading facility and the driver that all closures must be physically inspected prior to transportation.

column168: The origin terminal 089 stacked another DuPont pro 089-1905869 on top each other on the tail of the trailer. The skids were not secured properly and the movement in transit caused the box underneath the stacked skid to be crushed and the lid to pop. The release was noted as .5 LGA from the top of the package on the damage report. After interviewing the manager at the 089 terminal we recommended training and written warnings for both the dock worker and the supervisor. An email was sent to confirm the actions taken.  No exposures or injuries resulted before or during the incident. The release was managed in 30 minutes and no further actions are necessary.

column168: This was a return shipment form El Paso, TX. The freight moved through Dallas and was transferred to another trailer in Greensboro to move to destination. U/A to Winchester the release was noticed as soon as the door was opened. The dockworker noticed the odor. The trailer was unloaded to get to the product. A visual inspection revealed the skid had been pushed into a skid in front of the product at the previous terminal 017 causing 2 of the cartons to be crushed at the bottom. Two of the cans in the carton were leaking. The material was cleaned up and the cartons placed in a recovery drum. The carrier has 2 cartons containing 6 LGA for disposition. No exposures or injuries occurred as a result of the incident. The release was managed in 45 minutes and no further actions are necessary.

column169: MAKE SURE THAT THE LOAD IS SECURE BEFORE CLOSING OUT THE TRAILER.  PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  PLACE CUSHIONING BETWEEN ROWS/LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO BE EASILY DAMAGED.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column169: USE PROPER SAFE LOADING PROCEDURES WITH THE FORKLIFT WHILE LOADING A TRAILER.  PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING DRUMS OF LIQUIDS.  CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDSINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  REMOVE AND AVOID OBSTRUCTIONS IN LANE OF TRAVEL TO PREVENT DAMAGE AND UNSAFE SITUATIONS.  PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OR LIQUIDS AHEAD, HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. column168: TEIX 16112 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) on the repair track for a B-end wheel set replacement was reported dripping product at the A-end tank shell bottom near the rear draft gear plate. Dried product residue was observed on the lead A-end wheel axle and also on the inward facing wheel plates. A receptacle was placed under this area to catch any further product drippage. The exact origin of the leak source in the tank shell could not be readily determined. The shipper arranged for a replacement tank car for product transfer. The product in TEIX 16112 was transferred into TCIX 175201 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) without further incident on 3/25/09. After the product transfer was completed, no further product release was observed from TEIX 16112 and it was sent to a qualified repair shop for furtherance.  TEIX 16112's side specification stencil indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 1999 and next due in 2009.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A van trailer was preparing to depart for the intended waste disposal facility from Clean Harbors 10 day storage facility.  While doing his pretrip inspection, the driver noticed material leaking onto the trailer floor.  The facility's emergency response team was notified, they donned the appropriate PPE and entered the trailer.  Absorbent pads were placed on the trailer floor and the trailer was backed into the dock and the leaking drum was removed.  The drum was a salvage drum that had been used by the generator to overpack a leaking drum of acid that they had at their location.  The steel drum had corroded from the acid solution.  A plastic salvage drum was then used to overpack the material.  The absorbent pads were placed inside this drum and, after the trailer was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound, it was reloaded back onto the trailer and proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The shipper was notified that using a metal salvage drum was in this case inappropriate for the chromic acid solution.  The driver who picked up the drum at the origin location was instructed to be more aware of picking up salvage drums that may not be proper for the job.  The persons who handled the improperly packed salvage drum were all retrained in awareness of packaging requirements.

AN EMERGENCY RESPONSNE CONTRACTOR TEAM ASSRIVED TO CLEAN UP AND DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A STRESS FRACTURE IN THE TOTE CAUSING IT TO LEAK. THE DAMAGED EMPTY TOTE AND THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: SHIPPER TO SHIP IN STURDY CONTAINERS, DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING.  THE DURABILITY OF A TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION.  IMPORTANTLY THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE TOTES THAT SHOW SIGNS OF DETERIORATION MUST NOT ALLOWED TO BE TRANSPORTED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED.  DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN.

column168: ON MARCH 4TH, 09 @ 0930 - BASIC CHEMICAL SOLUTIONS IS GEISMER WAS NOTIFIED THAT TRAILER #242, DEPARTING THE PPG FACILITY IN WESTLAKE WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP CRASH BOX.  AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION, THE DRIVER DETERMINED THE PRESSURE VACUUM VALVE ON TOP OF THE TRAILER HAD FAILED ALLOWING SODIUM HYDROXIDE (CAUSTIC SODA) TO SEEP OUT OF THE VALVE INTO THE CRASH BOX.  THE DRIVER STOPPED ON SIDE OF THE ROAD JUST PAS THE GUARD DOCK ON PPG DRIVE.  PPG WAS NOTIFIED.  PPG NOTIFIED THE STATE POLICE.  APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL LEAKED FROM THE TRAILER ONTO PPG DRIVE.  THIS AREA OF ROAD WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DECONTAINMATED THE CLAMP MATERIAL WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED BY PPG EMPLOYEES.  THE TRAILER;S PRESSURE VACUUM VALVE WAS REMOVED AND A CAP WAS SECURED.  THIS ALLOWED THE TRAILER TO BE SPOTTED BACK INTO PPG'S YARD WAITING FOR A REPAIR.  THE TRAILER WAS PROPERLY REPAIRED AND RETURNED TO SERVICE THE NEXT MORNING.
column169: THE MANUFACTURER OF THE VALVE (PRESSURED VACUUM) SHIPPED A NEW SEAL KIT.  A LOCAL SERVICE COMPANY REBUILT THE VALVE AND PRESSURE TESTED IT.  IT PASSED THE INSPECTION AND THE VALVE WAS REPLACED BACK INTO SERVICE.

column168: Container was found to have a loose lid at our Newark N.J. facility. The lid was tightened on this container by personnel in Newark and it was placed in an overpack and shipped to destination. At an interim point Louisville KY an odor was detected and the overpack was observed by a supervisor along with another pail in the shipment on itsside. Thinking the pail was leaking he contacted safety and was instructed to isolate the trailer and contact a spill vendor. The spill vendor found the lid on the pail had failed to seal properly and the overpack lid was not secured tightly or the seal was defective allowing vapor to escape. There was no loss of liquid product only vapor. The spill vendor then overpacked the overpack containing the original 5 gallon pail and it was held in Louisville for disposition.This was prepared in response to missing info request on Tracking Number 2009040107.
column169: Product should have been held in Newark for disposition and not shipped to the destination. Supervisor needs to be retrained in proper handling of hazardous materials.

column168: BNSF 880375 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in queue at the fuel unloading track in the railyard was reported dripping product from the bottom outlet area. BNSF 880375 was carefully moved over the drip pan containment at the fuel track. Responders inspected BNSF 880375 and reported that the top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV) was closed and secured. The bottom outlet extension under the tank car was inspected and two of the four flange bolts appeared missing; product was leaking from this flanged connection. One bolt was absent and the other appeared to be broken off within the threaded connection. BNSF 880375 was unloaded in place. After BNSF 880375 was unloaded it remained over the containment area until no further product drips were evident.  A contractor's vacuum truck was used to capture the product spillage that remained atop the partially frozen ground. Impacted ground soil was excavated by a BNSF contractor and soil sampling initiated. All spillage recovered was placed into the used oil recovery system at this facility.   BNSF 880375 was forwarded to a qualified repair facility for repairs and failure analysis.  The specification stencil on BNSF 880375 indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2000.

column168: At 02:40 on March 21, 2009 a fully loaded Honeywell cargo tank carrying anhydrous hydrogen fluoride (AHF) was traveling southbound on Rt 33 in Wind Gap, PA when 2-3 deer appeared in the right lane heading toward the left travel lane. The driver attempted to avoid the deer by steering the vehicle to the right around the deer. The truck encountered the shoulder of the road and the rumble strips. Because of the sudden movement, the load began to surge causing the tractor to swerve from side to side. As the driver attempted to correct the movement and bring the vehicle back on the roadway, the rear wheels of the tractor broke traction, which added difficulty to controlling the vehicle. The tractor and trailer both overturned onto the passenger (right) side of the vehicle. The vehicle slid on its side for approximately 150 yards coming to rest against the Jersey barrier dividing the north and south lanes of the 4 lane road.    Continued on additional Sheet
column169: Our fleet of tractors is presently being upgraded. The safety features include electronic stability control, brighterheadlamps, and moose bars which protect the tractor from damage in the event of hitting a large animal on the road.Also, each tractor will be equipped with updated GPS communications as required by TSA for PIH materials. The tractors will have a rollover alarm which sends an automatic signal to the QualComm base. The MC312 tank performed well under the stressful conditions. The tank was thicker than required for the pressure rating (0.5 " vs0.325 " steel). We believe this was a critical factor in the tank survival. The new DOT412 tanks are expected to perform better because of design improvements on valving and lines. The DOT412 design also mandates 0.5"stainless steel which will perform better because of its enhanced ductile strength.

column168: A RETAIL OIL DELIVERY DRIVER TOOK HIS EYESE OFF THE ROAD TO REVIEW WRITTEN ROUTING INFORMATION.  DURING THIS TIME THE PASSENGER SIDE WHEELS LEFT THE HARD SURFACE OF THE ROAD AND ENTERED ONTO THE SOFT SHOULDER.  IN AN EFFORT TO RETURN TO THE ROAD SURFACE, THE DRIVER DID STEER SHARPLY TO THE LEFT.  THE STEERING ACTION DID CAUSE THE LIQUID IN THE CARGO TANK TO SHIFT.  THE MOMENTUM OF THE SHIFT IN COMBINATION WITH THE MOVERMENT OF THE LIQUID TO A HIGHER CENTER OF GRAVITY CAUSED THE TRUCK TO OVER TURN.  THE TRUCK DID ROLL A FULL TURN AND CAME TO REST ON ITS TIRES.  THE CARGO TANK BECAME DETACHED FROM THE CHASSIS AND CAME TO REST BESIDE THE CHASSIS.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CONTACT COMPANY PERSONAL TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  FURTHER INFORMATION WAS OBTAINED FROM A MOTORIST WHO WITNESSED THE ACCIDENT.  EMERGENCIES SERVICES WERE CONTACTED.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL.  THE CARGO TANK REMAINED IN TACT.  THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED AT NOT GREATER THAN FIVE GALLONS.  THE PRODUCT RELEASED CAME FROM A PORTION OF THE UNDER CARRIAGE PIPIMG.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOSS AND ITS ORIGIN OR RELEASE DURING THE ACCIDENT THE RELEASE AREA WAS LIMITED TO THE HARD SURFACE OF THE ROAD.  PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES WERE TAKEN BY RESPONDING PERSONAL TO CONFINE ANY POTENTIAL FURTHER RELEASE.  THE CONTENTS OF THE CARGO TANK WERE REMOVED SAFELY.  ADDITIONAL LIQUID PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE UNDER CARRIAGE PIPING WAS REMOVED.
column169: THE DVD "THE POINT OF NO RETURN-TANKER TRUCK ROLL OVER SAFETY" PROVIDED BY FEDERATED INSURANCE IS USED DURING THE DRIVING PORTION OF THE LEFFLER ENERGY REQUIRED HM TRAINING.  THE SECTION ALSO HIGHLIGHTS DISTRACTED DRIVING.  INCREASING THE FREQUENCY OF SUPERVISOR DELIVERY SAFETY AUDITS WILL HELP TO IDENTIFY DRIVING HABITS THAT ARE CONTRARY TO SAFE DRIVING PRACTICES.

TM and mechanic went to site with more oil dry and spill pads and cleaned up the site. Brent at Pantry was notified and was okay with our clean up. The state was notified by Steve Lucas at Action Environemtal. Did not seem to be any real damage to the parking lot. Driver was at fault and was suspended.
column169: Better training and proper use of equipment would have prevented this incident. The driver will be required to discuss this incident at the next safety meeting & point out his errors to the other drivers.

AT APPROXIMATELY 11:45 KEVIN DART WAS OFF LOADING A DELIVERY OF (12) CHLORINE CYLINDERS (150 LBS) TO THE BORO OF WELLSBORO.  HE WAS USING A RYDER RENTAL TRAILER WITH LIFT.  THIS WAS KEVIN FIRST TIME USING THIS PARTICULAR RENTAL AND WAS NOT FAMILIAR WITH IT AT ALL.  HE PLANNED TO MOVER THE CYLINDERS TO THE GROUND (2) AT A TIME WITH THE LIFT GATE WHILE HE HOLDS THEM.  THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED DURING HIS INITIAL TRIP TO THE GROUND WITH CYLINDERS.  AS DESCRIBED TO ME, KEVIN HIT THE CONTROL BUTTON COMMANDING THE GATE TO DESCEND AND IT DID JUST THAT IN AN IMMEDIATE, UNEXPECTED WAY CAUSING KEVIN TO LOSE HIS BALANCE AND CONTROL OF THE CYLINDERS.  ONE OF THE CYLINDERS THEN FELL OFF THE GATE TO THE GROUND LANDING DIRECTLY ON THE BONNET.  THE IMPACT WITH THE GROUND CRACKED THE BONNET AND BENT THE VALVE CAUSING THE VESSEL TO LEAK.  THE LEAK WAS UNCONTROLLED FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES.  KEVIN AND THE EMPLOYEE ON STAFF AT WELLSBORO ACTED FAST TO SECURE THE VESSEL AND DID SO BY APPLYING AND "A0KIT".  NO OUTSIDE AGENCIES WERE CALLED.
column169: THE INCIDENT CAN MOSTLY BE ATTRIBUTED TO THE FACT THAT KEVIN WAS USING EQUIPMENT HE WAS NOT FAMILIAR WITH.  ACTION TAKEN TO AVOID/PREVENT REOCCURRENCE ARE AS FOLLOWS; I HAD A DISCUSSION WITH KEVIN AND ALL OF OUR OTHER DRIVERS INFORMING THEM THAT WHEN USING A RENTAL FOR THE FIRST TIME OR ANY PIECE OF EQUIPMENT TO FIRST FAMILIARIZE THEMSELVES WITH THE UNTI COMPLETELY.  I WILL WORK ON A PROCEDURE WITH STEPS TO TAKE IN ADDITION TO THEIR PRE-TRIP THAT IS ALREADY IN PLACE THAT WILL MANDATE THIS FAMILIARIZATION.  I DON'T THINK ANY IMPROVEMENTS NEED TO BE MADE TO THE ACTUAL CONTAINER OF WAY TRANSPORT.  THE SYSTEM IN PLACE IS PROVEN TO WORK GREAT WHEN POTENTIAL FOR HUMAN ERROR IS REMOVED.

column168: This is a report of the tank car GATX 44376 leak incident of March 9, 2009. The car in question was located in our tank car area, which is enclosed and was hooked up to our offloading equipment. The Senior Chemist on duty, Mr. James Irving went to prepare the car for service at approximately 8:30 AM. When he opened the gas header valve on the turret he noticed a leak coming from the turret valve area and he informed the maintenance staff on duty. When the area was checked, it was discovered that the leak was not coming from the turret valves but from the manway. After attempting to try to stop the leak, they contacted Mr. Gerald Scales, Assistant Sewage Plant Laboratory Supervisor, who was responsible for the area. It was recommended to him to call in the available Hazmat team, as the leak could not be controlled. It should be noted that the leak did not set off the alarms for the area, which are set at a minimum of 1 ppm. At the same time, the vendor of the product, PVS Technologies was called in to provide assistance with the tank car.  The HAZMAT team arrived on the scene at about 9 AM and checked the tank car. When they saw that the leak could not be stopped the declared a level two situation and called in for more support. The representatives of PVS technologies arrived at approximately 10 AM. The Hazmat team, the WWTP maintenance personnel and the PVS representatives went to check the car. The S02 detectors in the room were all reading zero at this time. When the car was checked, it was found leaking underneath the manway in the area of the gas valve that was connected to the facility. A portable gas detector registered about 3 ppm at the leak area. All parties retreated to the Main control room to discuss what to do next. It was determined that the leak was coming from the gasket that the manway sat on. After some discussion it was decided by WWTP management that the safest way to handle this was to transfer the product to a nearby empty tank car and evacuate the leaking tank car as soon as possible. The platform was configured to move the liquid from on car to another while at the same time have the car being filled feed gas into the offloading system allowing the WWTP to stay in regulatory compliance with the Michigan Department of Environmental Quality (MDEQ). The transfer was started at about 2:30 PM and there were no incidents. The Hazmat team left shortly thereafter. The PVS representatives stated they would return the next day with personnel that could help patch the leak. The transfer of product was to take between twenty four (24) and forty eight (48) hours to complete.    PVS personnel arrived the next day with a maintenance expert, which examined the car and applied a patch to the manway area. When the car was checked for leaks with ammonia, no visible leaks were found. The tank car pressure was measured at 0 psi n the afternoon shift and the car was closed off. The vendor was notified on March 11 that the car was emptied and cl
