column168: Train crew of train NR-3 was weighing railcar GATX 71667 at Dow Chemical’s scale in Allyins Point, Connecticut, when they smelled a strange odor from one of the railcars. They notified a security guard at the plant who then contacted their inhouse response team. It was discovered that product was leaking from the thermometer well of this railcar. The leak was very small and was hard to detect with the naked eye, but when a gas meter was put into the dome area it registered a flammable mixture. Dow Chemical contacted the shipper and they had a Midland kit attached to the car so it could be unloaded. After the was unloaded the remaining residue had to be flared off before the car could be shipped to home shop for repairs. A company out of Philadelphia called React was brought in to flare the car and then the car was stenciled not to be reloaded and sent to home shop for repairs.

column168: OUR DRIVER MR. DALE SCHACT WAS STOPPED AT THE PILOT TRUCK STOP IN LONDON, OH.  HE WAS ENROUTE TO VEOLIA IN WEST CARROLLTON, OH.  UPON A LOAD CHECK AND VEHICLE INSPECTION, MR. SHAEF DETECTED THE SPILLAGE.  THE DRUM APPARENTLY HAD A "HIT" FROM LOADING OR TRANSFERRING.  PERHAPS A PALLET JACK.  THE ABRASION, OR CREASE, WAS AT THE LOWER 1ST RING ON THE DRUM.  MR. SCHAEL TURNED THE DRUM ON IT'S SIDE AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  BEFORE THIS WAS DONE, VEOLIA EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER WAS CALLED.  CLEAN UP CREW ARRIVED AND CLEARED SPILLAGE.  ARRIVED AT 14:45.  CLEAN UP AND OVERPACK OF STEEL SPILLAGE.  ARRIVED AT 14:45.  CLEAN-UP AND OVERPACK OF STEEL DRUM COMPLETED AT 15:50.  NONE OF THE SPILLAGE HIT THE GROUND ONLY THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.
column169: MR. DALE SCHAEF IS TRAINED IN HAZWOPER, HAZWOPER REFRESHERS, AND HAZ FAMILIARIZATION AND AWARENESS TRAINING TO LOOF FOR AND RECOGNIZE DEFICIENT OR QUESTIONABLE DRUMS.  THIS PARTICULAR LOAD WAS FULL TO VISIBLE CAPACITY OF DRUMS AND VARIOUS VESSELS OF WASTE.  IT WAS A DROP AND HOOK.  SO, OTHER THAN SECURING THE LOAD FOR SHIPMENT, THERE WOULD HAVE BEEN NO WAY TO CHECK THE SPECIFIC DRUM FOR THE ABRASION.  THE DRIVER'S QUICK RESPONSE PREVENTED A LARGER AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE AND MITIGATED THE SITUATION.

column168: Railroad Car # PGTX400263 was located on a track with in the Sierra Northern Railway, Oakdale Yards.  The car was parked and not moving at the time of the leak.  Train crews in the area reported to the railroad dispatcher this car to have liquid running out of dome on car.  Emergency services were notified, along with car shipper/owner. It was discovered that the valve stem on a liquid valve on the top of the dome was leaking on account of bad packing on the stem of the valve. Shipper/owners responded with a crew, who repaired the leaking liquid valve on the top of the tank car.  It is estimated that about 40 Gallons of product leaked from the defective valve and leached into the ground.  The leak was contained to an area of about five square feet under the center of the tank car. The shipper hired an outside contractor to handle remediation and clean up of dirt/ground in the area.  The shipper/owner, Etc'ra,Inc., is a division of Proctor and Gamble, who handled repairs for the rail tank car and the clean up, along with disposal of soils from the area under the tank car.  This soil consisted of about 30 Cubic Yards of material. The material was disposed of at a certified dump site and replaced with new materials.  Test were completed of all soilsin the area and found not to contain any material from the spill.  Tank car repairs consisted of removal of the valve and replacement with a new valve of like design.
column169: No suggestions to prevent recurrence, except for better inspections of cars by shipper prior to placing intotransportation.

OUR DRIVER (JEREMY RONQUILLO) WAS DELIVERING SOME OF OUR PRODUCT TO ANOTHER MULTI-CHEM FACILITY IN VERNAL, UT FOR THEIR USE IN THE FIELD.  WHILE IN TRANSIT ON CO HWY 139 APPROXIMATELY 18 MILES NORTH OF LOMA, CO, A SOUTH-BOUND PETEREBILT PULLING A TRAILER LOST CONTROL WHILE ENTERING A RIGHT-HAND CURVE AND ROLLED 1/4 TIMES AND COLLIDED WITH OUR VEHICLE WHICH WAS NORTH-BOUND.AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION, 3 OF THE 4 RIGID PLASTIC IBCS WERE DESTROYED OR SIGNIFICANTLY DAMAGED RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF 736 GALLONS OF 15% HYDROCHLORIC ACID, 85% WATER. JEREMY WAS ABLE TO NOTIFY AUTHORITIES AND HIS MANAGER OF THE ACCIDENT AND SPILL.THE MANAGER AND 3 OTHER EMPLOYEES WENT TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND POTASH FOR THE CLEANUP, THEY WERE ABLE TO GET THE HCL LEFT IN THE DAMAGED/DESTROYED IBCS TRANSFERRED TO NEW ICBS.  THE REST OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP WAS CONDUCTED BY ECOS WHO ARRIVED IN THE EARLY AFTERNOON ON THE DATE OF THE ACCIDENT.THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS EJECTED DURING THE ROLLOVER AND DIED AT THE SCENE.  OUR DRIVER SUSTAINED MINOR CUTS AND BRUISES.
column169: THERE WERE NO CHANGES IN TRAINING,PACKAGING OR OPERATING PROCEDURES THAT COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS ACCIDENT FROM MULTI-CHEM'S PERPECTIVE. OUR DRIVER WAS LIMITED IN THE AMOUNT OF EVASIVE VEHICLE MANEUVERS THAT HE COULD HAVE TAKEN DUE TO TERRAIN AND THE SIZE OF THE COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE THAT LOST CONTROL CAUSING THE ACCIDENT.

column168: THE TRAILER WAS LOADED AND PARKED IN THE SECURED LOT AT PSC IN BATON ROUGE FOR DELIVERY TO SUNBELT CHEMICAL ON 3/9/09.  ON 3/8/09 AT 08:00 EST AM PVS WAS NOTIFIED BY STATE HAZMAT POLICE OFFICE LEE LEWIS OF AN INCIDENT.  A PVS DRIVER ARRIVED ON SCENE TO ASSIST AROUND THE SAME TIME.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK BY CAPPING THE 1 INCH VENT LINE ON THE TRAILER BEFORE 08:30 EST.  OFFICIALS INDICATED THE LEAKING VALVE WAS CHANGED WHILE THEY WERE ONSITE.  THERE WAS A HOLE ON THE FEMALE SIDE OF THE VALVE AND IT HAD CRACKED.  EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO HANDLE THE NEUTRALIZATION AND REMEDIATION. 4-5 YARDS OF GRAVEL WERE NEUTRALIZED AND REMOVE BY EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL.
